Japan  set incentives for renewable
energy today, endorsing the rates proposed by a government panel
in April, according to a statement on the website of the
Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry.   Industry Minister Yukio Edano approved the subsidized
tariff of 42 yen (53 U.S. cents) a kilowatt-hour for 20 years
for solar energy, according to the statement. For wind, the rate
is 23.10 yen per kilowatt-hour for 20 years.  To contact the reporter on this story:
